body:
While optimizing a hot loop in an application which counts the number of `true` values in an sequence of `bool`s, I came up against some very unexpected differences between how functions which take `bool`s by-value and by-reference get optimized.

Here is a minimal godbolt link showing the issue: https://godbolt.org/z/e98Grvoeo

The godbolt contains two tabs, each containing a variant of:

```rust
pub struct T(u64);

impl T {
    pub fn add(&mut self, v: bool) {
        self.0 += v as u64;
    }

    pub fn add_all(&mut self, values: &[bool]) {
        values.iter().for_each(|&o| self.add(o));
    }
}
```

where the `v` arg of `add` is either by reference or by value. The by-reference version of `add_all` optimizes significantly better.  The vectorized portion (by-val on left, by-ref on right):

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/160242/158084853-65c2cb71-d392-45dd-a605-48f8c7cdde20.png)

Even the unvectorized remainder loop is simpler (by-val on left, by-ref on right):

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/160242/158084701-fedd2eb7-bd90-4dfb-868c-2f8bf95a15cf.png)

Here are a couple other versions of this same issue, at various stages of simplification from the actual application:

https://godbolt.org/z/d3hKvd1Mn
https://godbolt.org/z/9coEzax4T
